If such a response gets published, and I maybe publish a response of my own, readers may make up their own mind on whether my analytical claims in the article still seem reasonable.

I think this is an important response. When we do research on contemporary communities and people, it's important that we accept and encourage that people can "talk back" and respond. So I have encouraged them to write a response.

I should add for the sake of transparency that a couple of those who were involved in this process of halal regulation have told me that they disagree with my interpretations. They don't disagree on facts, but they disagree that it was not only (or mainly) about theology
This led to a fascinating development where things changed back and forth many times. I'll leave the rest of the details to article, for those that are interested.

But the idea that stunning is bad never completely left the minds of many Norwegian Muslims. This preoccupation also interacted with internal politics among Muslim organizations. Halal regulation can confer both status and money - so it's inevitably becomes contested

The Norwegian ban on stunning clearly mattered, and had an impact on the reasoning of Muslims in Norway. Recall Elster and "sour grapes": The fox decides that there's anyway not much point to eating the grapes he can't reach, as they are sour and not ripe https://t.co/NxyUPHXCdq
But this doesn't explain why there was so much back and forth, while the theological ideas stayed approximately the same. So we also need to look at social context!

How should we make sense of all this back and forth? The sources I consulted (written and oral) indicate that both theology and politics (in a broad sense) mattered. There is no denying that ideas about Islamic theology and right and wrong played a large part.

So I reveal a story I think is really fascinating, which nobody has written about before. The main body in charge of issuing halal regulations in Norway - The Islamic Council of Norway - actually changed their stance on stunning and halal 4-5 times. https://t.co/TBF87H9JwO
The challenge for Muslims in Norway is that their preferred method of slaughter - killing a conscious animal without pre-stunning - is not allowed in Norway. So what to do?

In this article I demonstrate that the answer may often be found someplace in between these two positions: both Islamic theology and social/political context may matter. This a boring and common-sensical  thing to say, of course, but it's still interesting to explore how and why

This kind of research claims are probably a reaction to an opposite and common idea in public discourse, that Muslims are kind of predetermined to act in certain ways because of what the Quran (or Islamic orthodoxy) says

The context is approximately this: In the research on Islam in Europe, some researchers have claimed that Islamic theology doesn't actually matter that much. What matters is social context, discrimination, Islamhopobia, political regulations, etc.

The topic of this article may seem narrow: halal regulations on Islamic slaughter, i.e. what conditions Muslims in Norway think must be in place in order to eat meat. But I use this to approach a broader question: How much does Islamic theology matter for what Muslims actualy do?
